President Biden has declared a major disaster in the state of Kansas and authorized federal assistance to support recovery efforts from severe storms, winds, tornadoes, and flooding that occurred from July 14 to July 21, 2023. The funding will be available to state, tribal, and local governments, as well as certain nonprofit organizations, for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The designated counties include Allen, Barton, Clark, Comanche, Edwards, Finney, Ford, Greeley, Johnson, Kearny, Pawnee, Rawlins, Rice, Russell, Stafford, Thomas, Wallace, Wichita, Woodson, and Wyandotte. Federal funding will also be provided for statewide hazard mitigation measures. Andrew P. Meyer from FEMA has been appointed to coordinate federal recovery operations in the affected areas. Further designations may be made if requested by the state and based on damage assessments. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.